    <title>Combined summary - Taro: A Taproot Asset Representation Overlay</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T18:39:31.326056+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-April/020205.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The article discusses the implementation of "miner-based commitments" in Bitcoin transactions to allow standardized commitments to be made at no additional cost. A mechanism could be created for standardized miner-based commitments, such as having a sorted merkle tree of commitments. However, users cannot control miner-based commitments, and there is a need for a payment mechanism for miners to include commitments.The article also introduces a new protocol called Taro, which allows the issuance of normal and collectible assets on the main Bitcoin chain. Taro uses Taproot script tree for extra asset metadata based on a Merkle Sum Sparse Merkle Tree (MS-SMT), allowing efficient proof of non-existence. Taro's scripting system allows programmatic unlocking/transfer of assets, and it follows the Unspent Transaction Output (UTXO) model used by Bitcoin. However, there are concerns about Taro's ability to handle conditional payments and potential for asset inflation if the UTXO does not change in a transaction.Despite these limitations, Taro's BIPs can be found on GitHub. Taro tokens are embedded in a virtual/overlay transaction graph that uses a chain of asset witnesses, allowing provable tracking of asset transfers across taproot outputs. The Lightning Network can also integrate with Taro for multi-hop transfers. Technical challenges still need to be addressed, but Taro offers exciting possibilities for asset issuance on the Bitcoin chain.During recent discussions, several issues related to the "utxo teleport" scheme and Taro's state transition model were raised. Johan and Olaoluwa Osuntokun discussed the shortcomings of the utxo teleport scheme, while Hiroki Gondo raised concerns about asset provenance verification in Taro's specifications. Laolu Osuntokun suggested orienting the proofs at the taproot output level to remove redundant data and generate a proof for a single leaf. Ruben Somsen also examined RGB extensively and believes that some of the issues he uncovered in that project also apply here. Ruben notes that there are some issues with the scripting expectations of Taro, which is described as being able to have its own scripting capabilities.The article discusses the limitations and tradeoffs of the Taro system, including its inability to consolidate multiple Taro coins' value into a single output and enforce special per-asset rules. The feasibility of adding a scripting language to Taro is also discussed, along with proposed solutions to issues such as the need for the location of the Taro tree inside the taproot tree to be deterministic for the verifier. The author suggests a concrete scheme to ensure that the Taro commitment is in a unique place within the Taro tree and proposes that a standardized algorithm for constructing a taproot tree is missing in the ecosystem. While the impact of the Taro commitment on items in the script tree itself isn't too bad, it may make sense to roll out a distinct BIP that carves out an explicit structure/split if applications/protocols start making more structured commitments in the tapscript tree.</summary>
